subSubSection.paragraph:
Antennae (
Figs 15–16, 19, 13–14
) comparatively long, almost reaching elytral half; scape with only apical seta, testaceous with metallic cupreous or green lustre; antennomeres 2–5 ochre-yellow to testaceous, often with faint metallic lustre on apices and on pedicel; antennomeres 7–11 (
Figs 13–14
) progressively blackened and becoming gradually shorter, but still elongate; last two antennomeres never distinctly dilated (normally shaped).

Aedeagus (
Fig. 20
) generally shaped as in other species of the genus, apical half conically attenuated and rather distinctly ventrally directed towards narrow, rounded apex; internal sac (
Fig. 21
) conspicuously armed with mostly distinctly sclerotized pieces, comprising basoventral spur with distinct projection, thin, composed basal sclerites connected with a membrane, long, longitudinal central spike surrounded with a membrane with finely cristate surface, long, narrow spike placed along dorsoapical orifice, and upper, moderately bent acute spike arising from the membranous area.
